<blockquote>
<p>( Im sorry Im a little confused with what your saying)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Hope seems to me to be clearly in the wrong here. She works for an extralegal conspiracy that enslaves and imprisons people, erases people's memories and indenties and all kinds of other heinous ends-justifying means. <em>If</em> those means are justified, it's only by a utilitarian appeal to the continued survival of human civilization. Personal revenge doesn't benefit the largest number of people, or really anybody. She also failed to declare her conflict of interest and let her personal life interfere with her work, which incidently also makes her a poor scientist, too. So we have an abuse of power over another for personal reasons, in direct violation of professional ethics. Seems clear-cut.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>One side being that you move on and deal with it personally and the other being deal with the problem directly.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well I've only killed a few people and murdered absolutely nobody so I know my answer. I haven't even killed that one guy who really does deserve it. Forgiveness is freeing a prisoner, and that prisoner is you, or something. Most people don't generally revenge-murder, it turns out, so this doesn't seem to be ambiguous for most&#8230;</p>

